ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 4
 shows the BET/BJH curves of CF and its modified forms, acid-treated CF and CQDs@CF which are used to analyze surface area and pore size. N2 adsorption − desorption isotherms at 77 K showed type IV Langmuir isotherms with H3 hysteresis loops ranging from 0.29 − 1P/Po, indicating a mesoporous structure.The H3 loops observed in the BET/BJH curves are attributed to the presence of uniform bottleneck pores with a narrow size distribution. Ads/Des plots (Fig. 4, curves a, b, c) show that the N2 adsorption amounts for CQDs@CF increased to 1.7991 compared to 0.8736, and 0.3864 cm3 g−1 for pristine and acid-treated CF samples respectively, indicating a significant improvement in term of surface area. The measured surface areas of the pristine CF, acid-treated CF, and CQDs@CF structures were found to be 0.12008, 0.52082, and 1.2024 m2/g, respectively. These results confirm that the surface area increased 10-fold when the CF was modified with CQDs (Table 1
). BJH analysis results (Fig. 4, curves d, e, f) revealed pore volumes of 0.00056113, 0.0013167, and 0.0027095 cm3 g−1 for pristine CF, acid − treated CF, and CQDs@CF, respectively. The enhanced porosity in the case of CQDs@CF could lead to an easy adsorption/desorption process due to effective contact with working solutions, fast distribution equilibrium, and increased adsorption capacity.
